@justinmc this is a blocker for one of my clients that wants rich text copy/paste. To copy/paste rich text we need to use super_clipboard because Flutter itself doesn't expose any non-plain-text clipboard APIs. However, Flutter doesn't give us any control over what copy and paste means when using the native context menu.

For example, this is where Flutter decides on behalf of all apps what "copy" means: https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/afba7d75b391a6b8015a2e437d74cf0f55036606/engine/src/flutter/shell/platform/darwin/ios/framework/Source/FlutterTextInputPlugin.mm#L1340

Can you please take another look at the priority level on this ticket? This limitation is likely a major blocker for all rich text editing on iOS at this point, given that no app can afford to use their own custom toolbar with the awful permission dialog that pops up. I doubt that this is much of a lift from an API work perspective, especially if the threading model has been merged and there's no risk of an async jump.

