From the codebase:
  /// An optional method to call when the user indicates they are done editing
  /// the text in the field. Will only be called if the input represents a valid
  /// [DateTime].
  final ValueChanged<DateTime>? onDateSubmitted;

 /// An optional method to call with the final date when the form is
  /// saved via [FormState.save]. Will only be called if the input represents
  /// a valid [DateTime].
  final ValueChanged<DateTime>? onDateSaved;

Since in the second scenario the value is becoming null, I don't think that is a valid DateTimeObject, hence it's not calling either of them to update... but the Flutter Team can comment on it

Let me give some more context:
In addition to the docs above, there is also this:

```dart
  /// Determines if an empty date would show [errorFormatText] or not.
  ///
  /// Defaults to false.
  ///
  /// If true, [errorFormatText] is not shown when the date input field is empty.
  final bool acceptEmptyDate;
```

From my understanding, when I indicate that I want an empty date to be accepted by the form, it should be considered a valid date in the `onDateSubmitted` and `onDateSaved` callbacks, because I would otherwise have no option to react on the user having deleted the input from the form field.

So in my opinion, the `onDateSubmitted` and `onDateSaved` callbacks should be of type `ValueChanged<DateTime?>?`

