![selectabletext](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/20254485/120792105-fd800780-c56f-11eb-8ad4-24cde0dedc9b.gif)

`setState()` is called for changing the text style in this example when the mouse pointer enters the region of the decorated `TextSpan` and when it exits there.  If it occurs while part of `SelectableText` is already selected, the selection is cancelled unexpectedly.

The yellow circle in the GIF animation means the mouse is being left-clicked.

## Steps to Reproduce

1. Copy and paste the code below to an editor.
2. Run the app.
3. Select part of the text and then hover the mouse pointer over the blue text.

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() => runApp(const App());

class App extends StatelessWidget {
  const App();

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return const MaterialApp(
      home: Scaffold(
        body: Padding(
          padding: EdgeInsets.all(16.0),
          child: _Text(),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

class _Text extends StatefulWidget {
  const _Text();

  @override
  _TextState createState() => _TextState();
}

class _TextState extends State<_Text> {
  var _isHovered = false;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return SelectableText.rich(
      TextSpan(
        children: [
          TextSpan(
            text: 'Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, ',
          ),
          TextSpan(
            text: 'sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt',
            onEnter: (_) => setState(() => _isHovered = true),
            onExit: (_) => setState(() => _isHovered = false),
            style: TextStyle(
              color: Colors.blue,
              decoration: _isHovered ? TextDecoration.underline : null,
            ),
