The location for the compose (mark) text on iOS is in `firstRectForRange`. There are two inputs to this, both of which come from the framework:
1. `_editableTransform`: an affine transform matrix that comes from the framework during composing.
2. `_markedRect`: the rect describing the composing range.

My guess is that this is almost certainly to do with `_markedRect` and if I were to hazard a guess, could possibly be due to [these lines](https://github.com/flutter/engine/blob/0ac2fc2a1d1c427759d4f3112d42cc08cd053ea8/shell/platform/darwin/ios/framework/Source/FlutterTextInputPlugin.mm#L1517-L1526):
```objc
1517     if (CGRectEqualToRect(_cachedFirstRect, kInvalidFirstRect)) {
1518       // If the width returned is too small, that means the framework sent us
1519       // the caret rect instead of the marked text rect. Expand it to 0.1 so
1520       // the IME candidates view show up.
1521       double nonZeroWidth = MAX(_markedRect.size.width, 0.1);
1522       CGRect rect = _markedRect;
1523       rect.size = CGSizeMake(nonZeroWidth, rect.size.height);
1524       _cachedFirstRect =
1525           CGRectApplyAffineTransform(rect, CATransform3DGetAffineTransform(_editableTransform));
1526     }
```

Notice that we tweak the width, but not the height in the case where the rect width is zero? If the height were also zero, we'd be setting the rect to a 0.1 width, zero height rect, and the candidates menu would potentially be positioned on top of the character. If that is indeed the case, the more interesting question is why we're getting a zero-zero rect at all when a character has been typed -- my guess is a race condition since the compose rect update happens asynchronously, but iOS's text input APIs are generally synchronous.

@justinmc In our application we have a DateField component which is a a TextField with a onTap function to call the showDatePicker() of flutter. To block the user to type a date we set it on readonly. When the user try to submit the form when an error occurs we call the focusScope to focus the first error. As the textfield is readonly if the component has an error, the scroll doesn't happens to show the error which is an accessibility issue for us. Also there is a difference for us between a readonly component and a disabled component, in our case the component is not disabled we just can't allow the user to type in the field.

Here is an other video to show what I mean. I show you the behavior of our DateField component and also of our form.
