I noticed that when we explicitly set textDirection: TextDirection.rtl, the issue does not appear. However, this only works reliably when the text is entirely in one language. If the text is mixed (for example, containing both Arabic and English in the same sentence), it causes layout/display problems.

Here’s a minimal reproducible example:

```
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return const MaterialApp(
      debugShowCheckedModeBanner: false,
      home: Scaffold(
        body: Center(
          child: SelectableText(
            'Depending on how much text you have, you might would have to go to the second level for this.\n\nاعتمادًا على مقدار النص الذي لديك، قد يتعين عليك الانتقال إلى المستوى الثاني لهذا.',
            textDirection: TextDirection.rtl,
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```


So while forcing RTL fixes single-language text, it doesn’t handle mixed Arabic/English cases correctly.

